  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, many countries have specific laws and regulations designed to combat money laundering. In the United States, key anti-money laundering (AML) laws include the Bank Secrecy Act and the USA PATRIOT Act. These laws require financial institutions to:\n\n1. Implement customer identification programs\n2. Report suspicious transactions\n3. Maintain transaction records\n4. Conduct due diligence on customers\n5. Screen for potential terrorist and criminal activities\n\nInternationally, organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards for preventing money laundering and terrorist financing. Most developed countries have comprehensive AML legal frameworks with significant penalties for violations.\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income by tracking and reporting suspicious financial activities.",
